  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in virtually every country around the world. It is a criminal offense that involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The goal is to make the money appear as though it comes from a legitimate source.\n\nMoney laundering is often associated with other criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption. Governments and international organizations have established strict laws and regulations to combat money laundering, and financial institutions are required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to detect and report suspicious activities.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines, asset forfeiture, and lengthy prison sentences.",
